Despite a small turn out of just less than 15 people, the LGBTIQA+ society this morning participated in the peaceful #MarchAndAsk-LGBTIQA. The small group braved the scorching heat as they marched from Church Square to the Women Living Heritage Centre at Sammy Marks, for human rights. The full acronym for LGBTIQA+ is (Gay, Bisexual, Trans, Intersex, Queer, Asexual, Agender Acromantic+ - other diverse sexual orientations and gender identities. Vibrant participants were singing and chanting as they marched for the worthy cause, with police keeping a close watch. Their songs were drawing spectators to their apartment balconies and out of shops. Strategic Organiser at the Tassie Foundation who is also one of the organisers Ntako Mangani said: “We want general society to understand the LGBTIQA+ because we are living in a very diverse society. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window.  "We need to understand each other because if we don’t then it will be very difficult for us to live together. “The march will also create a platform for people to ask each other any question whether comfortable or uncomfortable,” he told Pretoria News. Manganyi said they had expected more than a thousand people to take part. “The response was great on social media but i’m thinking there were challenges with transport.”